+# Solution for Issue: Query: Translate List.Exists
+
+## Root Cause
+
+`List<T>.Exists(Predicate<T> match)` was not recognized by EF Core's query normalization pipeline, causing queries like `c.Orders.Exists(o => o.OrderDate != someDate)` to fail translation to SQL.
+
+The existing normalization visitor (`QueryableMethodNormalizingExpressionVisitor`) already handles similar collection method rewrites — for example, normalizing `list[x]` to `ElementAt(x)` and `ICollection<T>.Contains` to queryable `Contains` — but had no handler for `List<T>.Exists`.
+
+`List<T>.Exists(Predicate<T>)` is semantically identical to `Enumerable.Any<T>(IEnumerable<T>, Func<T, bool>)`. The only structural difference is that `Predicate<T>` and `Func<T, bool>` are different delegate types with the same signature.
+
+## Change Description
+
+Added a normalization branch in `QueryableMethodNormalizingExpressionVisitor.VisitMethodCall` (in `src/EFCore/Query/Internal/QueryableMethodNormalizingExpressionVisitor.cs`) that detects calls to `List<T>.Exists(predicate)` and rewrites them to `Enumerable.Any<T>(source, predicate)`.
+
+The predicate lambda is reconstructed with a `Func<T, bool>` delegate type (instead of `Predicate<T>`) so it is compatible with `EnumerableMethods.AnyWithPredicate`. The rewritten call then re-enters `VisitMethodCall`, which picks it up via the existing `TryConvertEnumerableToQueryable` path and converts it to `Queryable.Any`, which EF Core already knows how to translate to SQL `EXISTS`.
+
+## Files Edited
+
+- `src/EFCore/Query/Internal/QueryableMethodNormalizingExpressionVisitor.cs` — added `List<T>.Exists` → `Enumerable.Any` normalization
+- `test/EFCore.Specification.Tests/Query/NorthwindMiscellaneousQueryTestBase.cs` — added `List_Exists_translated_to_Any` test
+- `test/EFCore.SqlServer.FunctionalTests/Query/NorthwindMiscellaneousQuerySqlServerTest.cs` — added SQL assertion for the new test
